EDA Train data¶

Introduction¶

  • This notebook contains initial data exploration, analysis and visualisations. Pythonatic aimed to discover trends, patterns, or to check assumptions with the help of statistical summary and graphical representations.`

Data sourcing¶

  • The train data is from source provided by the client: https://trein.fwrite.org/idx/DVS.html. This is an unofficial archive travel information Dutch public transport. They got this information from APIs from the NS and NDOV Loket. This website is from Adriaan van Natijne and is giving the licences it needs to function legally. The data there matches the accuracy quality criteria mentioned in the beginning of the document.

Data Quality Analysis Conclusion¶

Data Source¶

  • At the start of the project Ordina pointed us to a train information archive to give us a headstart. Briefly looking into it, the archive seems to be entirely maintained by train hobbyists working together in an online group. The data is registered as open source and the only language for the data documentation or discussions thereof is Dutch.

The data in the archive is, according to the group themselves, acquired directly from the NS API and another open source archive called NDOV Loket

Accuracy¶

  • Due to the archive being sourced directly from the NS API, it is in NS's interest to maintain it to be as accurate as possible. The delays for example can be measured in seconds.

  • Conclusion: Due to the facts above we found the data to be accurate enough and representative of reality for our purposes.

Completeness¶

  • Looking at the data we find the only missing values to be station codes which are just shortened versions of the name of the Station a train is departing from. We cannot be sure this data is as complete as the one present in the NS API currently. It also only includes the year of 2016. We also found that many of the features that we were hoping for (A train's next stop, cause of delay, or number of stops per journey) are missing from this data.

  • Conclusion: Despite these facts, we find the data to be complete enough for our scope. Were the scope to be larger we would address this by investigating if more complete data could be found elsewhere, perhaps by scraping from the NS API itself.

Reliability¶

  • Looking at the data documention in the archive we find it was sourced and filtered rigorously by its maintaining group. We also found the archive itself to be licensed under an open-source copyright, and believe this adds to the data's reliability. The archive is still actively updated as of May 2022 but this could of course change in the future.

  • Conclusion: From these facts we find the data to be reliable and trustworthy enough for our scope.

Relevance¶

  • The data includes delay duration and the time of departure which are very much relevant to our project's goal. However as mentioned above it does not include some features we concluded to also be relevant to this project's goal. As train delays could be influenced by all kinds of factors from weather to train pilot negligence or a very lengthy boarding process, we do find this for example to be relevant.

  • Conclusion: We find the data to be relevant enough for our project, but we can certainly see how it could be much more relevant for predicting delays.

Timeliness¶

  • The data we will handle is limited to the year of 2016. Ordina specifically wanted us to use the data from 2016, we assume presumably because there was less data which makes it more manageable for students but also due to Covid-19 in later years having an impact on train travel. There is a chance that train companies in our data, such as NS have grown significantly. In turn this could impact all kinds of factors that influence how delays happen, what causes them and how long they last.

  • Conclusion: Right now in 2022 this particular data is 6 years old, which we find to be a large enough period that the landscape might've changed entirely. We find this data to not be representative enough for making future predictions, however we assume the patterns we notice below during EDA to be representative of an overal trend. Were we to have more time we could address this by applying our current EDA methods to other years to make more accurate conclusions.

#First I make a date from the date planned departure, then i make it a string in a new column for i can split it into 2 columns 
#and make the date alone a date, i also delete the str column i used for splitting the date and time
March['Train Departure Planned']=pd.to_datetime(March['Train Departure Planned'], format="%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ")
March['Train Departure Planned1']=March['Train Departure Planned'].astype(str)
March[['DepartureDatePlanned','DepartureTimePlanned']]= March['Train Departure Planned1'].str.split(' ', expand = True)
March['DepartureDatePlanned']=pd.to_datetime(March['DepartureDatePlanned'])
March.drop('Train Departure Planned1', axis=1, inplace=True)
March
#then i make the depature time a time delta (Actually want to make it a normal time format)
March['DepartureTimePlanned'] = March.apply(lambda row: pd.to_datetime(row.DepartureDatePlanned).time(), axis=1)
print(March.info())
March
#then i basically do the same but for the actual departure
March['Train Departure Actual']=pd.to_datetime(March['Train Departure Actual'], format="%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ")

March

September['Train Departure Planned']=pd.to_datetime(September['Train Departure Planned'], format="%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ")
September['Train Departure Planned1']=September['Train Departure Planned'].astype(str)

from datetime import timedelta

delta = 0
# Defying a function, that will calculate the percentage
def percentage(part, whole):
  return 100 * float(part)/float(whole)

# The total train departures (rows) (January)
total = len(January)
# The total delays, where minute is bigger than 0 (January)
delays = len(January[January['Train_Delay'] > delta])
perc = percentage(delays,total)

# Results
print('The count of delays: {}'.format(delays))
print('The total train departures count: {}'.format(total))
print('Percentage of delay for January: {:.6f}'.format(perc))

The count of delays: 2046304
The total train departures count: 5458998
Percentage of delay for January: 37.484974

The percentage is 37%.

# Percentage calculation
#Delay duration for the whole month per train company

#First grouping the delays with the different train company
compdelays = January[January['Train_Delay'] > delta].groupby(['Train_Company'])['Train_Delay'].count().reset_index()
# Then adding the percentage of delays for each company
compdelays['Percentage (of total)'] = compdelays['Train_Delay'] / total * 100
# Then adding the percentage of delays between the companies (so the sum of the percentage for each company should be 100%)
compdelays['Percentage (of companies)'] = compdelays['Train_Delay'] / delays * 100
# Sorting by most delays
compdelays = compdelays.sort_values(by="Train_Delay", ascending=False)

NaNs per month¶

In this step we can go through each month and see how many nan values are there. For that, first we need to create an array that will hold every month.

In [73]:
months = [January,February,March,April,May,June, July, August, September, October, November, December]

Then we can create a array that will hold all the nan values. In a for loop we can go through each month and add every feature that have NaN values to the array.

In [74]:
total_nans = []

# loop that goes through the months of 2016
for i, month in enumerate(months):
    m = i + 1 # the number of the month, + ` because index starts with 0
    nans = month.isna().sum()[month.isna().sum() > 0]
    
    total_nans.append(nans)
    # Showing the features with the amount of nans for each month
    print("For month {}: \n  {}".format(m,nans))

Time groups¶

  • Time groups represent the different rush hours during the day. The rush hours are early morning, morning, between, afternoon and night.
In [ ]:
from dateutil import parser #used for parsing datetime columns
# Creating a column that will hold the actual planned departure time
df['Train_Departure_Planned_Time'] = df.apply(lambda row: parser.parse(row.Train_Departure_Planned).time(), axis=1)
In [ ]:
# Removing the : from the planned departure time
df["Train_Departure_Planned_Time"] = df["Train_Departure_Planned_Time"].astype(str)
df['Train_Departure_Planned_Time'] = df['Train_Departure_Planned_Time'].str.replace(':', '', regex=False) 
df["Train_Departure_Planned_Time"] = df["Train_Departure_Planned_Time"].astype(int)
In [ ]:
# create Time groups
conditions = [
    #Night
    (df['Train_Departure_Planned_Time'] > 190000) & (df['Train_Departure_Planned_Time'] <= 240000),
    
    #Early Morning
    (df['Train_Departure_Planned_Time'] >= 0) & (df['Train_Departure_Planned_Time'] < 60000),
    
    #Morning Rush Hour
    (df['Train_Departure_Planned_Time'] >= 60000) & (df['Train_Departure_Planned_Time'] <= 100000),
    
    #Between Rush hours
    (df['Train_Departure_Planned_Time'] > 100000) & (df['Train_Departure_Planned_Time'] < 150000),
    
    #Afternoon Rush hour
    (df['Train_Departure_Planned_Time'] >= 150000) & (df['Train_Departure_Planned_Time'] <= 190000)
]

# create a list of the values we want to assign for each condition
values = ['Night', 'Early_Morning', 'Morning_Rush_Hour', 'Between_Rush_hours', 'Afternoon_Rush_hour']

# create a new column and use np.select to assign values to it using our lists as arguments
df['Time_Group'] = np.select(conditions, values)

# display updated DataFrame
df.head()
In [ ]:
# Creating a time group target, that will contain only numbers, mapped with the real rush hours, so we can visualize it in scatter plots.
df['Time_Group_Target'] = df['Time_Group'].map({"Morning_Rush_Hour":0,"Between_Rush_hours":1,'Afternoon_Rush_hour':2,"Early_Morning":3,"Night":5})
df['Train_Delay'] = January['Train_Delay']
In [ ]:
# Plotting the 5 different rush hours for the day
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))
scatter = plt.scatter(df['Train_Delay'], df['Train_Departure_Planned_Time'], c=df['Time_Group_Target'], cmap='rainbow')

# Adding handles for the legend
handles, labels = scatter.legend_elements(prop="colors", alpha=0.9)
plt.legend(handles, ["Morning Rush Hour","Between Rush Hour", "Afternoon Rush Hour","Early Morning","Night"], loc="upper right", title="Rush Hours")
# Adding labels + title
plt.xlabel("Train Delay")
plt.ylabel("Planned Departure Time")
plt.title("Rush hours during the day")
  • From the scatterplot we can see the 5 different rush hours for the day. Y shows the time of the day, starting from 12am and X shows the duration of each delay. The first rush hour, early morning, starts from 12am and ends at 6am, then the morning rush hour starts and ends at 10:00, and so on.

# Negative delays
  • Another think to look at is the negative delays. We noticed that there are some train departures that have negative delay, which means the train departured earlier than the planned time. This will interfere with the machine learning model, therefore we should change all negative delay to 0.
In [20]:
# Here we are grouping the delay with the actual departure time and sum it
TotalDelayDay = df.groupby('Train_Departure_Actual')['Train_Delay_Seconds'].sum().reset_index()
# The negative delay will store only the rows that have delay below 0
NegativeDelay = TotalDelayDay[TotalDelayDay['Train_Delay_Seconds'] < 0].reset_index()

Conclusion¶

Taking into account everyone's insights and conclusions as well as Ordina's advice from our previous proposal meeting we decided to start modeling on a small dataset. Because all of the missing values are station codes which are a shortened version of the station name we can simply ignore the station codes to remove the missing values.

We decided to focus on a filtered dataset of the month of January with only a popular train destination as an end Destination (Schiphol Airport). Filtering it by Schiphol Airport as end destination in January we see above that the only train types are Intercitys, Sprintters and extra trein and the only train company is NS. This means using this dataset will be appropriate and manageable as we keep it small and filtered. It will also eliminate all companies and destinations that are not relevant here as a side benefit.
